===Etymology===
{{OE.}} [[īġland]].  The S was added by confusion with French ''[[isle]]'', which is not related but is instead from Latin ''[[insula]]''.  Cognate with German ''[[Aue]]'', "water-meadow", and Latin ''[[aqua]]''.  Compare German ''[[Eiland]]'', Old Norse ''[[eyland]]'', and English ''[[ey]]'' as in [[Anglesey]], [[Bardsey]], [[Ely]].

